## ğŸŒŸ 1. Coin Change Problem (Greedy version)

**Concept:**
Tumhe kuch coin denominations diye gaye hote hain (jaise â‚¹1, â‚¹2, â‚¹5, â‚¹10) aur ek amount banana hota hai (say â‚¹27).
Goal hota hai â€“ **minimum number of coins** use karke total amount banana.

**Approach:**
Greedy algorithm har step par **sabse bada coin** choose karta hai jo remaining amount se chhota ya equal ho.
Example:
Amount = 27, coins = {10, 5, 2, 1}

* 10 â†’ 10 â†’ 5 â†’ 2 â†’ (Total = 27)
  Coins used = 4.

**Use kab karte hain:**
Jab tumhe *minimum coins / minimum notes* chahiye ho aur coin denominations standard ho (jaise Indian currency).
ğŸ‘‰ **Important:** Greedy approach har baar optimal answer nahi deta unless coin system canonical ho (jaise Indian coins).
Non-standard coins ke liye **Dynamic Programming (DP)** version use hota hai.

**Keywords to identify in exam:**

> "Make change", "minimum coins/notes", "denominations", "specific amount"
> â†’ **Use Coin Change Problem.**

---

## ğŸ’° 2. Fractional Knapsack Problem

**Concept:**
Ek bag hai jisme limited weight capacity hai (say 50 kg). Tumhare paas items hain har ek ka *value* aur *weight*.
Goal hai â€“ **maximum profit/value** banana bag ki limit ke andar.

**Fractional meaning:** Tum item ka **part** bhi le sakte ho (e.g. aadha item).

**Approach:**
Greedy approach:

1. Calculate value/weight ratio (profit per weight).
2. Sort items by descending ratio.
3. Fill bag with highest ratio items first, fractionally if needed.

**Use kab karte hain:**
Jab **fractional items allowed** ho (e.g. petrol, gold, rice, etc. â€” divisible items).
Non-fractional (0/1) case me DP lagta hai.

**Keywords to identify in exam:**

> "Maximum profit", "capacity", "can take fraction", "divide item"
> â†’ **Use Fractional Knapsack.**

---

## ğŸŒ² 3. Minimum Spanning Tree (MST)

**Concept:**
Given a connected weighted graph â€” tumhe sab vertices ko connect karna hai **minimum total edge weight** ke sath, bina cycle ke.
Yaani ek **tree** banana hai jisme sab nodes connected ho aur total cost kam ho.

**Do main algorithms hain:**

### (a) Primâ€™s Algorithm

* **Start from one vertex**.
* Har step pe **minimum weight edge** choose karo jo tree ko naye vertex se connect kare.
* Similar to Dijkstra but for MST.

### (b) Kruskalâ€™s Algorithm

* **Sort all edges** by weight.
* Add smallest edge if it **does not form a cycle** (use unionâ€“find).
* Continue till nâˆ’1 edges added.

**Use kab karte hain:**

* Jab question me likha ho â€œ**connect all cities with minimum cost**â€, â€œ**lay cable network**â€, â€œ**road construction with minimum cost**â€.
  â†’ **Use MST.**

**Prim vs Kruskal:**

| Feature       | Primâ€™s                | Kruskalâ€™s          |
| ------------- | --------------------- | ------------------ |
| Starts from   | A single vertex       | All edges (sorted) |
| Data used     | Adjacency matrix/list | Edge list          |
| Suitable for  | Dense graphs          | Sparse graphs      |
| Detects cycle | Automatically avoided | Needs unionâ€“find   |

**Keywords to identify in exam:**

> â€œMinimum cost to connectâ€, â€œno cyclesâ€, â€œconnect all verticesâ€, â€œspanning treeâ€
> â†’ **Use MST (Primâ€™s or Kruskalâ€™s).**

